MH  - Middle Aged
MH  - Prognosis
MH  - Radiography
MH  - Sex Factors
MH  - Time Factors
OID - PIP: 745129
OID - POP: 00024565
OAB - Nearly 7% of women develop breast cancer during their lifetime. The incidence and 
      mortaility rates had remained the same for over 30 years. In the last decade, 
      although the incidence had increased, a small decrease in mortality has been 
      recorded and improvement in survival time attained. Risk factors are sex, age, 
      familial history of breast or endometrial cancer, parity, and previous cancer in 
      the other breast. Age at 1st pregnancy is more significant than number of births. 
      Genetic predisposition is important. Hormones are thought to be mainly 
      potentiators. The average cancer has been present 6-8 years before it can be 
      palpated. True early diagnosis means discovery in the preclinical stage. 
      Mammography, xerography, and thermography have aided in early diagnosis. Such 
      yearly examinations are indicated for high risk patients and physical examination 
      every 6 months. Modified radical mastectomy gives 10-year survival and local 
      recurrent rates nearly as good as the radical operation and much better 
      functional and cosmetic results. A simple mastectomy on the other side may also 
      be advisable. Radiotherapy alone has a poor 10-year survival rate. It amy reduce 
      local recurrence rates. Palliative hormone and chermotherapy have extended 
      survival time. Immunotherapy is still in the experimental stage but holds the 
      best promise for the future. Patients with good host resistance have the better 
      prognosis.
